  "text": "Body Weight Gain and Food Consumption. The relatively nonselective nAChR agonist nicotine is well known to have effects on body mass, a phenomenon well illustrated by the lower average weight of smokers. These effects of nicotine have been linked to changes in feeding behavior and increased energy metabolism [CITATION_1] , presumably mediated by nAChR subtypes that have been identified in relevant pathways in the CNS and periphery [CITATION_2] . Because the db Ϫ mouse expresses an obese phenotype, we probed the role of the ␣7 nAChR subtype in regulating weight gain by monitoring the effects of the ␣7-selective agonist TC-7020 on body mass. At the end of 7 weeks of treatment, between ages 3 and 10 weeks, weight gain in the vehicle control db Ϫ obese groups was significantly greater (p Ͻ 0.05) than that of lean vehicle controls (Fig. 5A) as expected. By comparison, weight gain was significantly reduced (p Ͻ 0.05) in the ␣7 agonist-treated db Ϫ obese mice (Fig. 5A) . The daily food intake in vehicle control obese groups was significantly greater (p Ͻ 0.05) than that of lean vehicle controls and was significantly lower (p Ͻ 0.05) in the TC-7020-treated obese mice than in the obese controls (Fig. 5B) . The food consumption and body mass of the db ϩ lean mice were unaffected by TC-7020 or MLA, confirming that the compounds were not producing toxic effects that altered food intake or weight. However, when the selective ␣7 antagonist MLA was given concurrently with TC-7020, the obese mice showed no significant differences in body weight gain or food intake compared with the obese vehicle-treated controls (Fig. 6, A and B) , confirming that the reduced weight gain is mediated by ␣7 nAChRs.",
